---
import ActBreak from '../ActBreak.astro';
import FigurePlate from '../FigurePlate.astro';
import Action from './Action.astro';
---

<ActBreak
  roman="Act IV"
  title="Does It Actually"
  accent="Work?"
  tease="Seven findings, six random seeds, one standing rule: the evidence file decides, not the narrative."
  id="act-4"
/>

<section class="section-divider" id="loadability">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">07</span> First test</div>
    <h2>Can you place a thought at all?</h2>

    <p>
      Start with the gentlest possible experiment: don't write anything — just <em>ask</em>.
      Tell the model to hold a concept in mind — <em>fire</em>, <em>river</em>, <em>storm</em> —
      and then check its journal with the lens: did the concept actually show up where it should?
    </p>

    <p>
      The answer turned out to be a story about <strong>size</strong>, and about
      <strong>surgery</strong>. A 4-billion-parameter model manages it barely — the concept
      appears about <strong>1 time in 10</strong>, though that's still ten times what chance
      predicts. Its big sibling, at 27 billion parameters, succeeds
      <strong>more than half the time</strong>. And a model that had been <em>pruned and
      distilled</em> — compressed for efficiency, same size as the first —
      scores <strong>exactly zero</strong>. The journal's structure survives compression;
      the ability to take dictation does not.
    </p>

    <div class="callout amber">
      <div class="callout-title">The unsettling detail</div>
      <p>
        Efficiency surgery is standard industry practice — nearly every deployed small model has
        been through it. This result says such surgery can quietly remove a capability nobody was
        measuring. What else gets cut that we don't have instruments for yet?
      </p>
    </div>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_loadability"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 4"
      alt="Grouped bar chart of instructed hit-rate against a shuffled null for three models"
      caption="Instructed loading across three models: 0.10 at 4B (vs a 0.0104 chance floor, p ≈ 10⁻⁴), 0.55 at 27B (clearing the pre-registered 0.5 bar, dashed line), and 0.00 for the pruned-and-distilled twin. Hatched bars: what chance alone would produce."
      gates={["gate_L1", "gate_L1b", "gate_L2"]}
    />
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-divider" id="instrument" style="padding-top:0;">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">08</span> Second test</div>
    <h2>Listen at the chest, not the mouth</h2>

    <p>
      Before writing anything, one more discovery about <em>reading</em> — the one this whole
      toolkit stands on. A doctor doesn't diagnose a heart by listening to the patient's voice;
      she puts the stethoscope on the chest. The field's standard instrument had been doing the
      equivalent of listening at the model's <strong>mouth</strong> — its final output layer.
      Aim it there and a journal <em>full of content</em> reads as empty: zero, across every
      concept tested.
    </p>

    <p>
      Aim the same kind of instrument at the <strong>journal itself</strong> — the band's own
      exit — and the content appears at once. Where it matters most, at <em>subtle</em> doses
      (think: covert manipulation someone is trying to hide), the band-targeted instrument detects
      <strong>twice as much</strong> as the mouth-targeted one. Anyone can hear a shout. This
      stethoscope hears the whisper.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_articulation"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 5"
      alt="Per-layer read-out curves for the fitted lens and a no-training control"
      caption="The legibility gradient is a property of the model, not an artifact of the instrument: a control read-out with no fitted transport recovers the same rising curve (ρ = 0.607 vs 0.639; both p = 2×10⁻⁴)."
      gates={["gate_L7_articulation_null"]}
    />

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_lens_baseline"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 10"
      alt="Detection rate across write doses for band-targeted versus final-output instruments"
      caption="Head-to-head at n = 80 paired trials. At the subtle dose (α = 0.1): band-targeted 0.475 vs final-output 0.2375 — twenty detections only the band instrument caught, against one the other way (p = 2.1×10⁻⁵). At loud doses the two converge. One honest footnote: the pre-registered gap criterion (≥0.3) was missed by 0.0625, so the stronger claim was withdrawn."
      gates={["gate_L22_lens_headtohead", "gate_L22_floor_*"]}
    />
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-divider" id="core" style="padding-top:0;">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">09</span> The headline result</div>
    <h2>Write by the rules, and the mind follows</h2>

    <p>
      Now, finally, the pen — used exactly as the rulebook says. Write a concept the model can
      articulate. Write it in the journal's own coordinates. Write <em>only when the writer
      pauses</em>. Verify by reading back. Stop before the freedom budget runs out.
    </p>

    <p>
      Result: the concept surfaces in the model's actual writing in about
      <strong>a third of generations</strong> — versus a fifth if you simply ask it politely
      (the strongest fair comparison). The advantage held at <strong>every one of six
      independent random seeds</strong>; the odds of that by luck are 1 in 64 (p = 0.016). And
      every single run stayed inside the freedom budget. The model is steered, not bent.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_core"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 6"
      alt="Two panels: lift and advantage per seed; entropy budget compliance per seed"
      caption="The core result at six seeds. Left: how often the concept surfaced (blue) and the edge over polite asking (orange); dashed line marks the pre-registered bar. Right: the freedom budget — every seed inside ±0.5 nats (dashed lines)."
      gates={["gate_L11_rep", "gate_L11_rep_s2024", "gate_L11_rep_s31415", "gate_L11_rep_s999"]}
    />

    <div class="callout amber">
      <div class="callout-title">Honest asterisk</div>
      <p>
        The <em>direction</em> of the effect is proven; its <em>size</em> is not. The mean edge is
        +0.100, but it clears the pre-registered size bar at only 3 of 6 seeds — so the paper
        claims the sign, not the magnitude, and so does this page. A pleasant surprise on the
        side: steering costs no speed (24.8–25.0 tokens/s steered vs 19.7 baseline).
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      What does one of these episodes look like from the inside? The paper's answer is the map
      below — one real decode, layer by layer, with the write landing in a pause just before the
      word <em>fire</em> surfaces. Right after it: the same kind of episode, replayed live.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_thought"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 16"
      alt="Heatmap of journal legibility by layer and position in one decode, with the write event marked"
      caption="One steered thought, mapped. Shading: how legible each layer is at each moment of the decode (measured, not illustrative). The red arrow is the write — placed at an undecided moment; the journal's exit row records the read-back acceptance."
      gates={["gate_L7_articulation_null"]}
    />
  </div>
</section>

<Action />

<section class="section-divider" id="timing">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">11</span> Why timing wins</div>
    <h2>The whisper economy</h2>

    <p>
      Why bother waiting for pauses? Why not just write constantly? Because writes aren't free —
      and it turns out a well-timed whisper beats a monologue on efficiency,
      <strong>every single time it was measured</strong>. Across all six test conditions, the
      timed approach delivered <strong>2.3× more effect per write</strong>, recovering two-thirds
      of the constant-writing result while doing less than a third of the writing.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_timing"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 7"
      alt="Two panels comparing effect and writes per generation across timing strategies"
      caption="Timing strategies compared across write strength. Left: how often the concept surfaces. Right: how many writes each strategy spends. The timed arm gets ~60% of the constant arm's effect at a third of its writes — within budget."
      gates={["gate_L18_l8redo"]}
    />

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_efficiency"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 11"
      alt="Effect per write for timed versus constant writing across six conditions"
      caption="Effect per write, timed vs constant, across six seed-by-strength conditions. Timed wins all six; mean ratio 2.32×."
      gates={["gate_L22_benchmark"]}
    />
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-divider" id="transfer" style="padding-top:0;">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">12</span> Does it travel?</div>
    <h2>The settings die; the recipe survives</h2>

    <p>
      A method that only works on one model is a curiosity. So: take everything tuned on model A
      and transplant it, unchanged, onto model B. It <strong>collapses</strong> — the effect all
      but vanishes. Model B's internal geometry is roughly ten times "quieter"; settings tuned
      for one anatomy are meaningless on another, like moving a piano's sheet music to a violin
      and wondering why it sounds wrong.
    </p>

    <p>
      But the doctrine contains its own fix, and it's one line: <strong>write louder exactly in
      proportion to how quiet the model's geometry is</strong>. Recalibrated by that rule alone —
      no re-tuning, no search — the method hits full strength on the new model, scales smoothly
      with dose, and holds at four seeds. The constants don't transfer. The <em>law</em> does.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_recipe"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 8"
      alt="Calibrated steering versus polite asking at four seeds, with the uncalibrated transplant marked"
      caption="Transfer to the second model at four seeds: calibrated writes (blue) vs polite asking (orange). The dashed line is what blind transplanting achieved — 0.05, barely above nothing."
      gates={["gate_L13_recipe", "gate_L14_multiseed"]}
    />

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_scaling"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 9"
      alt="Dose-response curves for two models on a logarithmic axis"
      caption="The two-model dose law on a log axis, spanning ~1.5 orders of magnitude. The working strengths differ by 10× — in exactly the direction the calibration rule predicts."
      gates={["gate_L14_amp", "gate_L15_amp_joint", "gate_L16_fine"]}
    />

    <details class="expand">
      <summary>For researchers: one more integration — writing from a cold associative memory</summary>
      <div class="expand-body">
        <p>
          The write direction needn't come from the analytic formula. A completely
          <strong>untrained</strong> modern-Hopfield associative store (the CittaStore — no stored
          patterns, no training) steers within budget at all three seeds (lifts 0.44/0.56/0.44),
          matching the analytic path exactly at two seeds and differing by a single concept-hit —
          the metric's quantisation unit — at the third. Reported as an integration proof, not a
          superiority claim: the strict equivalence criterion failed on that margin, and the gate
          says so.
        </p>
        <FigurePlate
          name="fig_l20"
          figNo="Paper Fig. 12"
          alt="Cold associative-store recall versus the analytic write direction at three seeds"
          caption="Cold associative store vs analytic write direction. Two seeds match exactly; the third differs by one concept-hit, in the cold store's favour."
          gates={["gate_L20_confirm", "gate_L20_s42", "gate_L20_s123", "gate_L20_s777"]}
        />
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>
